#!/bin/sh

PROMPT="
Collect data that I request, below, and combine it into a morning brief formatted as html.

Print the brief to standard out in html. Use the style below.
Hyperlink article titles and other information on the web that you refer to.

Style: Editorial briefing / newspaper aesthetic. Georgia serif body text, #F5F5F0 warm off-white background, #111 text, max-width 780px, padding 28px 36px, box-sizing: border-box, no margins collapsed weirdly.

Header: Bold uppercase title in #1B3A6B, 22px, letter-spacing 0.04em. 3px solid #1B3A6B bottom border. Small uppercase muted dateline below in #555, 12px, letter-spacing 0.08em.

Section labels: Colored pill badges — inline-block, 11px, uppercase, letter-spacing 0.12em, bold, 2px border-radius, 3px 8px padding. Assign a distinct background color per section (dark green, burgundy, purple, slate, etc.) with #fff text. No generic gray for all sections.

Tables: Full-width, border-collapse: collapse. Three-column rows: a small right-aligned muted number column (12px, #aaa, width ~20px), a bold linked title column (#111, no underline at rest, underline on hover), and an italic muted summary column (13.5px, #444). Rows separated by 1px solid #d0d0ca; no border on the last row.

General: No shadows. No gradients. No rounded corners on containers. Sparse vertical rhythm with margin-bottom: 24px between sections. Print-like and editorial throughout.

Respond with raw HTML only.
Do not output markdown, code fences, or explanations. Just the HTML document starting with <!DOCTYPE html>.
Do not narrate or explain what you are doing.
The first line of your output must be <!DOCTYPE html> .
The last line of your output must be </html> .
Everything in between those must be valid html.

Use web search for articles from Canary Media and NPR, as those sites often will not allow direct access.

Requested data:
- top 3 articles from Canary Media (https://www.canarymedia.com/), one summary per article, of 15 words or less, per article.
- top 3 articles from NPR (https://www.npr.org/), one summary, of 15 words or less, per article.
- An estimate, expressed as a percentage, and a discussion of length 50 to 70 words about the probability of severe storms over North Dakota in the next 7 days, in the area between Bismark and Dickinson. Ignore all risks not directly associated with severe storms, such as fire and wind. To make your estimate, review https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/exper/day4-8/, https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/day3otlk.html, https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/day2otlk.html, https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/day1otlk.html, https://forecast.weather.gov/showsigwx.php?warnzone=NDZ033&warncounty=NDC089&firewxzone=NDZ033&local_place1=3+Miles+ENE+Dickinson+Theodore+Roosevelt+Regional+Airport+ND&product1=Hazardous+Weather+Outlook, and https://forecast.weather.gov/showsigwx.php?warnzone=NDZ035&warncounty=NDC015&firewxzone=NDZ035&local_place1=Bismarck%20ND&product1=Hazardous+Weather+Outlook&lat=46.8083&lon=-100.7837 . Use your judgement to create the requested estimate and discussion.

If you encounter problems, try web search or other work arounds.

If you report both content from articles and information on your own activites, put the content first and the information on your activities at the very end in a PREPARATION NOTES section.

This is an automated script and you should not ask questions because I will not be able to answer them.
"

/home/ubuntu/.nvm/versions/node/v24.15.0/bin/claude --allowedTools WebFetch,WebSearch -p "$PROMPT" | sed -n '/<\!DOCTYPE/,$ p'
